constructor.description:
Creates a `lodash` object which wraps `value` to enable implicit method
chain sequences. Methods that operate on and return arrays, collections,
and functions can be chained together. Methods that retrieve a single value
or may return a primitive value will automatically end the chain sequence
and return the unwrapped value. Otherwise, the value must be unwrapped
with `_#value`.

Explicit chain sequences, which must be unwrapped with `_#value`, may be
enabled using `_.chain`.

The execution of chained methods is lazy, that is, it's deferred until
`_#value` is implicitly or explicitly called.

Lazy evaluation allows several methods to support shortcut fusion.
Shortcut fusion is an optimization to merge iteratee calls; this avoids
the creation of intermediate arrays and can greatly reduce the number of
iteratee executions. Sections of a chain sequence qualify for shortcut
fusion if the section is applied to an array of at least `200` elements
and any iteratees accept only one argument. The heuristic for whether a
section qualifies for shortcut fusion is subject to change.

Chaining is supported in custom builds as long as the `_#value` method is
directly or indirectly included in the build.

In addition to lodash methods, wrappers have `Array` and `String` methods.

The wrapper `Array` methods are:
`concat`, `join`, `pop`, `push`, `shift`, `sort`, `splice`, and `unshift`

The wrapper `String` methods are:
`replace` and `split`

The wrapper methods that support shortcut fusion are:
`at`, `compact`, `drop`, `dropRight`, `dropWhile`, `filter`, `find`,
`findLast`, `head`, `initial`, `last`, `map`, `reject`, `reverse`, `slice`,
`tail`, `take`, `takeRight`, `takeRightWhile`, `takeWhile`, and `toArray`

The chainable wrapper methods are:
`after`, `ary`, `assign`, `assignIn`, `assignInWith`, `assignWith`, `at`,
`before`, `bind`, `bindAll`, `bindKey`, `castArray`, `chain`, `chunk`,
`commit`, `compact`, `concat`, `conforms`, `constant`, `countBy`, `create`,
`curry`, `debounce`, `defaults`, `defaultsDeep`, `defer`, `delay`,
`difference`, `differenceBy`, `differenceWith`, `drop`, `dropRight`,
`dropRightWhile`, `dropWhile`, `extend`, `extendWith`, `fill`, `filter`,
`flatMap`, `flatMapDeep`, `flatMapDepth`, `flatten`, `flattenDeep`,
`flattenDepth`, `flip`, `flow`, `flowRight`, `fromPairs`, `functions`,
`functionsIn`, `groupBy`, `initial`, `intersection`, `intersectionBy`,
`intersectionWith`, `invert`, `invertBy`, `invokeMap`, `iteratee`, `keyBy`,
`keys`, `keysIn`, `map`, `mapKeys`, `mapValues`, `matches`, `matchesProperty`,
`memoize`, `merge`, `mergeWith`, `method`, `methodOf`, `mixin`, `negate`,
`nthArg`, `omit`, `omitBy`, `once`, `orderBy`, `over`, `overArgs`,
`overEvery`, `overSome`, `partial`, `partialRight`, `partition`, `pick`,
`pickBy`, `plant`, `property`, `propertyOf`, `pull`, `pullAll`, `pullAllBy`,
`pullAllWith`, `pullAt`, `push`, `range`, `rangeRight`, `rearg`, `reject`,
`remove`, `rest`, `reverse`, `sampleSize`, `set`, `setWith`, `shuffle`,
`slice`, `sort`, `sortBy`, `splice`, `spread`, `tail`, `take`, `takeRight`,
`takeRightWhile`, `takeWhile`, `tap`, `throttle`, `thru`, `toArray`,
`toPairs`, `toPairsIn`, `toPath`, `toPlainObject`, `transform`, `unary`,
`union`, `unionBy`, `unionWith`, `uniq`, `uniqBy`, `uniqWith`, `unset`,
`unshift`, `unzip`, `unzipWith`, `update`, `updateWith`, `values`,
`valuesIn`, `without`, `wrap`, `xor`, `xorBy`, `xorWith`, `zip`,
`zipObject`, `zipObjectDeep`, and `zipWith`

The wrapper methods that are **not** chainable by default are:
`add`, `attempt`, `camelCase`, `capitalize`, `ceil`, `clamp`, `clone`,
`cloneDeep`, `cloneDeepWith`, `cloneWith`, `deburr`, `divide`, `each`,
`eachRight`, `endsWith`, `eq`, `escape`, `escapeRegExp`, `every`, `find`,
`findIndex`, `findKey`, `findLast`, `findLastIndex`, `findLastKey`, `first`,
`floor`, `forEach`, `forEachRight`, `forIn`, `forInRight`, `forOwn`,
`forOwnRight`, `get`, `gt`, `gte`, `has`, `hasIn`, `head`, `identity`,
`includes`, `indexOf`, `inRange`, `invoke`, `isArguments`, `isArray`,
`isArrayBuffer`, `isArrayLike`, `isArrayLikeObject`, `isBoolean`, `isBuffer`,
`isDate`, `isElement`, `isEmpty`, `isEqual`, `isEqualWith`, `isError`,
`isFinite`, `isFunction`, `isInteger`, `isLength`, `isMap`, `isMatch`,
`isMatchWith`, `isNaN`, `isNative`, `isNil`, `isNull`, `isNumber`,
`isObject`, `isObjectLike`, `isPlainObject`, `isRegExp`, `isSafeInteger`,
`isSet`, `isString`, `isUndefined`, `isTypedArray`, `isWeakMap`, `isWeakSet`,
`join`, `kebabCase`, `last`, `lastIndexOf`, `lowerCase`, `lowerFirst`,
`lt`, `lte`, `max`, `maxBy`, `mean`, `meanBy`, `min`, `minBy`, `multiply`,
`noConflict`, `noop`, `now`, `nth`, `pad`, `padEnd`, `padStart`, `parseInt`,
`pop`, `random`, `reduce`, `reduceRight`, `repeat`, `result`, `round`,
`runInContext`, `sample`, `shift`, `size`, `snakeCase`, `some`, `sortedIndex`,
`sortedIndexBy`, `sortedLastIndex`, `sortedLastIndexBy`, `startCase`,
`startsWith`, `subtract`, `sum`, `sumBy`, `template`, `times`, `toInteger`,
`toJSON`, `toLength`, `toLower`, `toNumber`, `toSafeInteger`, `toString`,
`toUpper`, `trim`, `trimEnd`, `trimStart`, `truncate`, `unescape`,
`uniqueId`, `upperCase`, `upperFirst`, `value`, and `words`

parameters.name: value
parameters.description: The value to wrap in a `lodash` instance.

functions.name: runInContext
functions.description: Create a new pristine `lodash` function using the `context` object.

functions.name: chunk
functions.description:
Creates an array of elements split into groups the length of `size`.
If `array` can't be split evenly, the final chunk will be the remaining
elements.

returns.description: Returns the new array containing chunks.

functions.name: compact
functions.description:
Creates an array with all falsey values removed. The values `false`, `null`,
`0`, `""`, `undefined`, and `NaN` are falsey.

returns.description: Returns the new array of filtered values.

functions.name: concat
functions.description:
Creates a new array concatenating `array` with any additional arrays
and/or values.

functions.name: drop
functions.description: Creates a slice of `array` with `n` elements dropped from the beginning.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of elements to drop.

functions.name: dropRight
functions.description: Creates a slice of `array` with `n` elements dropped from the end.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of elements to drop.

functions.name: dropRightWhile
functions.description:
Creates a slice of `array` excluding elements dropped from the end.
Elements are dropped until `predicate` returns falsey. The predicate is
invoked with three arguments: (value, index, array).

functions.name: dropWhile
functions.description:
Creates a slice of `array` excluding elements dropped from the beginning.
Elements are dropped until `predicate` returns falsey. The predicate is
invoked with three arguments: (value, index, array).

functions.name: fill
functions.description:
Fills elements of `array` with `value` from `start` up to, but not
including, `end`.

**Note:** This method mutates `array`.

functions.name: findIndex
functions.description:
This method is like `_.find` except that it returns the index of the first
element `predicate` returns truthy for instead of the element itself.

returns.description: Returns the index of the found element, else `-1`.

functions.name: findLastIndex
functions.description:
This method is like `_.findIndex` except that it iterates over elements
of `collection` from right to left.

returns.description: Returns the index of the found element, else `-1`.

functions.name: flatten
functions.description: Flattens `array` a single level deep.

functions.name: flattenDeep
functions.description: Recursively flattens `array`.

functions.name: flattenDepth
functions.description: Recursively flatten `array` up to `depth` times.

functions.name: fromPairs
functions.description:
The inverse of `_.toPairs`; this method returns an object composed
from key-value `pairs`.

functions.name: first
functions.description: Gets the first element of `array`.

functions.name: indexOf
functions.description:
Gets the index at which the first occurrence of `value` is found in `array`
using [`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons. If `fromIndex` is negative, it's used as the
offset from the end of `array`.

returns.description: Returns the index of the matched value, else `-1`.

functions.name: initial
functions.description: Gets all but the last element of `array`.

functions.name: join
functions.description: Converts all elements in `array` into a string separated by `separator`.

functions.name: last
functions.description: Gets the last element of `array`.

functions.name: lastIndexOf
functions.description:
This method is like `_.indexOf` except that it iterates over elements of
`array` from right to left.

returns.description: Returns the index of the matched value, else `-1`.

functions.name: nth
functions.description:
Gets the nth element of `array`. If `n` is negative, the nth element
from the end is returned.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The index of the element to return.

functions.name: pullAll
functions.description:
This method is like `_.pull` except that it accepts an array of values to remove.

**Note:** Unlike `_.difference`, this method mutates `array`.

functions.name: pullAllBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.pullAll` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element of `array` and `values` to generate the criterion
by which they're compared. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

**Note:** Unlike `_.differenceBy`, this method mutates `array`.

functions.name: pullAllWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.pullAll` except that it accepts `comparator` which
is invoked to compare elements of `array` to `values`. The comparator is
invoked with two arguments: (arrVal, othVal).

**Note:** Unlike `_.differenceWith`, this method mutates `array`.

functions.name: remove
functions.description:
Removes all elements from `array` that `predicate` returns truthy for
and returns an array of the removed elements. The predicate is invoked
with three arguments: (value, index, array).

**Note:** Unlike `_.filter`, this method mutates `array`. Use `_.pull`
to pull elements from an array by value.

returns.description: Returns the new array of removed elements.

functions.name: reverse
functions.description:
Reverses `array` so that the first element becomes the last, the second
element becomes the second to last, and so on.

**Note:** This method mutates `array` and is based on
[`Array#reverse`](https://mdn.io/Array/reverse).

functions.name: slice
functions.description:
Creates a slice of `array` from `start` up to, but not including, `end`.

**Note:** This method is used instead of
[`Array#slice`](https://mdn.io/Array/slice) to ensure dense arrays are
returned.

functions.name: sortedIndex
functions.description:
Uses a binary search to determine the lowest index at which `value`
should be inserted into `array` in order to maintain its sort order.

returns.description:
Returns the index at which `value` should be inserted
 into `array`.

functions.name: sortedIndexBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.sortedIndex` except that it accepts `iteratee`
which is invoked for `value` and each element of `array` to compute their
sort ranking. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

returns.description:
Returns the index at which `value` should be inserted
 into `array`.

functions.name: sortedIndexOf
functions.description:
This method is like `_.indexOf` except that it performs a binary
search on a sorted `array`.

returns.description: Returns the index of the matched value, else `-1`.

functions.name: sortedLastIndex
functions.description:
This method is like `_.sortedIndex` except that it returns the highest
index at which `value` should be inserted into `array` in order to
maintain its sort order.

returns.description:
Returns the index at which `value` should be inserted
 into `array`.

functions.name: sortedLastIndexBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.sortedLastIndex` except that it accepts `iteratee`
which is invoked for `value` and each element of `array` to compute their
sort ranking. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

returns.description:
Returns the index at which `value` should be inserted
 into `array`.

functions.name: sortedLastIndexOf
functions.description:
This method is like `_.lastIndexOf` except that it performs a binary
search on a sorted `array`.

returns.description: Returns the index of the matched value, else `-1`.

functions.name: sortedUniq
functions.description:
This method is like `_.uniq` except that it's designed and optimized
for sorted arrays.

returns.description: Returns the new duplicate free array.

functions.name: sortedUniqBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.uniqBy` except that it's designed and optimized
for sorted arrays.

returns.description: Returns the new duplicate free array.

functions.name: tail
functions.description: Gets all but the first element of `array`.

functions.name: take
functions.description: Creates a slice of `array` with `n` elements taken from the beginning.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of elements to take.

functions.name: takeRight
functions.description: Creates a slice of `array` with `n` elements taken from the end.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of elements to take.

functions.name: takeRightWhile
functions.description:
Creates a slice of `array` with elements taken from the end. Elements are
taken until `predicate` returns falsey. The predicate is invoked with
three arguments: (value, index, array).

functions.name: takeWhile
functions.description:
Creates a slice of `array` with elements taken from the beginning. Elements
are taken until `predicate` returns falsey. The predicate is invoked with
three arguments: (value, index, array).

functions.name: uniq
functions.description:
Creates a duplicate-free version of an array, using
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons, in which only the first occurrence of each
element is kept.

returns.description: Returns the new duplicate free array.

functions.name: uniqBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.uniq` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element in `array` to generate the criterion by which
uniqueness is computed. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

returns.description: Returns the new duplicate free array.

functions.name: uniqWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.uniq` except that it accepts `comparator` which
is invoked to compare elements of `array`. The comparator is invoked with
two arguments: (arrVal, othVal).

returns.description: Returns the new duplicate free array.

functions.name: unzip
functions.description:
This method is like `_.zip` except that it accepts an array of grouped
elements and creates an array regrouping the elements to their pre-zip
configuration.

parameters.name: array
parameters.description: The array of grouped elements to process.

returns.description: Returns the new array of regrouped elements.

functions.name: unzipWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.unzip` except that it accepts `iteratee` to specify
how regrouped values should be combined. The iteratee is invoked with the
elements of each group: (...group).

parameters.name: array
parameters.description: The array of grouped elements to process.

parameters.name: iteratee
parameters.description:
The function to combine
 regrouped values.

returns.description: Returns the new array of regrouped elements.

functions.name: zipObject
functions.description:
This method is like `_.fromPairs` except that it accepts two arrays,
one of property identifiers and one of corresponding values.

functions.name: zipObjectDeep
functions.description: This method is like `_.zipObject` except that it supports property paths.

functions.name: chain
functions.description:
Creates a `lodash` wrapper instance that wraps `value` with explicit method
chain sequences enabled. The result of such sequences must be unwrapped
with `_#value`.

functions.name: tap
functions.description:
This method invokes `interceptor` and returns `value`. The interceptor
is invoked with one argument; (value). The purpose of this method is to
"tap into" a method chain sequence in order to modify intermediate results.

functions.name: thru
functions.description:
This method is like `_.tap` except that it returns the result of `interceptor`.
The purpose of this method is to "pass thru" values replacing intermediate
results in a method chain sequence.

functions.name: every
functions.description:
Checks if `predicate` returns truthy for **all** elements of `collection`.
Iteration is stopped once `predicate` returns falsey. The predicate is
invoked with three arguments: (value, index|key, collection).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if all elements pass the predicate check,
 else `false`.

functions.name: filter
functions.description:
Iterates over elements of `collection`, returning an array of all elements
`predicate` returns truthy for. The predicate is invoked with three
arguments: (value, index|key, collection).

functions.name: find
functions.description:
Iterates over elements of `collection`, returning the first element
`predicate` returns truthy for. The predicate is invoked with three
arguments: (value, index|key, collection).

functions.name: findLast
functions.description:
This method is like `_.find` except that it iterates over elements of
`collection` from right to left.

functions.name: flatMap
functions.description:
Creates a flattened array of values by running each element in `collection`
thru `iteratee` and flattening the mapped results. The iteratee is invoked
with three arguments: (value, index|key, collection).

functions.name: flatMapDeep
functions.description:
This method is like `_.flatMap` except that it recursively flattens the
mapped results.

functions.name: flatMapDepth
functions.description:
This method is like `_.flatMap` except that it recursively flattens the
mapped results up to `depth` times.

functions.name: each
functions.description:
Iterates over elements of `collection` and invokes `iteratee` for each element.
The iteratee is invoked with three arguments: (value, index|key, collection).
Iteratee functions may exit iteration early by explicitly returning `false`.

**Note:** As with other "Collections" methods, objects with a "length"
property are iterated like arrays. To avoid this behavior use `_.forIn`
or `_.forOwn` for object iteration.

functions.name: eachRight
functions.description:
This method is like `_.forEach` except that it iterates over elements of
`collection` from right to left.

functions.name: includes
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is in `collection`. If `collection` is a string, it's
checked for a substring of `value`, otherwise
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
is used for equality comparisons. If `fromIndex` is negative, it's used as
the offset from the end of `collection`.

functions.name: map
functions.description:
Creates an array of values by running each element in `collection` thru
`iteratee`. The iteratee is invoked with three arguments:
(value, index|key, collection).

Many lodash methods are guarded to work as iteratees for methods like
`_.every`, `_.filter`, `_.map`, `_.mapValues`, `_.reject`, and `_.some`.

The guarded methods are:
`ary`, `chunk`, `curry`, `curryRight`, `drop`, `dropRight`, `every`,
`fill`, `invert`, `parseInt`, `random`, `range`, `rangeRight`, `repeat`,
`sampleSize`, `slice`, `some`, `sortBy`, `split`, `take`, `takeRight`,
`template`, `trim`, `trimEnd`, `trimStart`, and `words`

functions.name: orderBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.sortBy` except that it allows specifying the sort
orders of the iteratees to sort by. If `orders` is unspecified, all values
are sorted in ascending order. Otherwise, specify an order of "desc" for
descending or "asc" for ascending sort order of corresponding values.

functions.name: reduce
functions.description:
Reduces `collection` to a value which is the accumulated result of running
each element in `collection` thru `iteratee`, where each successive
invocation is supplied the return value of the previous. If `accumulator`
is not given, the first element of `collection` is used as the initial
value. The iteratee is invoked with four arguments:
(accumulator, value, index|key, collection).

Many lodash methods are guarded to work as iteratees for methods like
`_.reduce`, `_.reduceRight`, and `_.transform`.

The guarded methods are:
`assign`, `defaults`, `defaultsDeep`, `includes`, `merge`, `orderBy`,
and `sortBy`

functions.name: reduceRight
functions.description:
This method is like `_.reduce` except that it iterates over elements of
`collection` from right to left.

functions.name: reject
functions.description:
The opposite of `_.filter`; this method returns the elements of `collection`
that `predicate` does **not** return truthy for.

functions.name: sample
functions.description: Gets a random element from `collection`.

functions.name: sampleSize
functions.description:
Gets `n` random elements at unique keys from `collection` up to the
size of `collection`.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of elements to sample.

functions.name: shuffle
functions.description:
Creates an array of shuffled values, using a version of the
[Fisher-Yates shuffle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher-Yates_shuffle).

functions.name: size
functions.description:
Gets the size of `collection` by returning its length for array-like
values or the number of own enumerable string keyed properties for objects.

functions.name: some
functions.description:
Checks if `predicate` returns truthy for **any** element of `collection`.
Iteration is stopped once `predicate` returns truthy. The predicate is
invoked with three arguments: (value, index|key, collection).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if any element passes the predicate check,
 else `false`.

functions.name: after
functions.description:
The opposite of `_.before`; this method creates a function that invokes
`func` once it's called `n` or more times.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of calls before `func` is invoked.

functions.name: ary
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func`, with up to `n` arguments,
ignoring any additional arguments.

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to cap arguments for.

functions.name: before
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func`, with the `this` binding and arguments
of the created function, while it's called less than `n` times. Subsequent
calls to the created function return the result of the last `func` invocation.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of calls at which `func` is no longer invoked.

examples:
jQuery(element).on('click', _.before(5, addContactToList));
// => allows adding up to 4 contacts to the list

functions.name: curry
functions.description:
Creates a function that accepts arguments of `func` and either invokes
`func` returning its result, if at least `arity` number of arguments have
been provided, or returns a function that accepts the remaining `func`
arguments, and so on. The arity of `func` may be specified if `func.length`
is not sufficient.

The `_.curry.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic builds,
may be used as a placeholder for provided arguments.

**Note:** This method doesn't set the "length" property of curried functions.

functions.name: curryRight
functions.description:
This method is like `_.curry` except that arguments are applied to `func`
in the manner of `_.partialRight` instead of `_.partial`.

The `_.curryRight.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic
builds, may be used as a placeholder for provided arguments.

**Note:** This method doesn't set the "length" property of curried functions.

functions.name: debounce
functions.description:
Creates a debounced function that delays invoking `func` until after `wait`
milliseconds have elapsed since the last time the debounced function was
invoked. The debounced function comes with a `cancel` method to cancel
delayed `func` invocations and a `flush` method to immediately invoke them.
Provide an options object to indicate whether `func` should be invoked on
the leading and/or trailing edge of the `wait` timeout. The `func` is invoked
with the last arguments provided to the debounced function. Subsequent calls
to the debounced function return the result of the last `func` invocation.

**Note:** If `leading` and `trailing` options are `true`, `func` is invoked
on the trailing edge of the timeout only if the debounced function is
invoked more than once during the `wait` timeout.

See [David Corbacho's article](https://css-tricks.com/debouncing-throttling-explained-examples/)
for details over the differences between `_.debounce` and `_.throttle`.

parameters.name: wait
parameters.description: The number of milliseconds to delay.

parameters.name: options.leading
parameters.description: Specify invoking on the leading edge of the timeout.

parameters.name: options.maxWait
parameters.description: The maximum time `func` is allowed to be delayed before it's invoked.

parameters.name: options.trailing
parameters.description: Specify invoking on the trailing edge of the timeout.

functions.name: flip
functions.description: Creates a function that invokes `func` with arguments reversed.

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to flip arguments for.

functions.name: memoize
functions.description:
Creates a function that memoizes the result of `func`. If `resolver` is
provided, it determines the cache key for storing the result based on the
arguments provided to the memoized function. By default, the first argument
provided to the memoized function is used as the map cache key. The `func`
is invoked with the `this` binding of the memoized function.

**Note:** The cache is exposed as the `cache` property on the memoized
function. Its creation may be customized by replacing the `_.memoize.Cache`
constructor with one whose instances implement the
[`Map`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-properties-of-the-map-prototype-object)
method interface of `delete`, `get`, `has`, and `set`.

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to have its output memoized.

parameters.name: resolver
parameters.description: The function to resolve the cache key.

functions.name: negate
functions.description:
Creates a function that negates the result of the predicate `func`. The
`func` predicate is invoked with the `this` binding and arguments of the
created function.

functions.name: once
functions.description:
Creates a function that is restricted to invoking `func` once. Repeat calls
to the function return the value of the first invocation. The `func` is
invoked with the `this` binding and arguments of the created function.

functions.name: rest
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with the `this` binding of the
created function and arguments from `start` and beyond provided as
an array.

**Note:** This method is based on the
[rest parameter](https://mdn.io/rest_parameters).

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to apply a rest parameter to.

parameters.name: start
parameters.description: The start position of the rest parameter.

functions.name: spread
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with the `this` binding of the
create function and an array of arguments much like
[`Function#apply`](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-function.prototype.apply).

**Note:** This method is based on the
[spread operator](https://mdn.io/spread_operator).

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to spread arguments over.

parameters.name: start
parameters.description: The start position of the spread.

functions.name: throttle
functions.description:
Creates a throttled function that only invokes `func` at most once per
every `wait` milliseconds. The throttled function comes with a `cancel`
method to cancel delayed `func` invocations and a `flush` method to
immediately invoke them. Provide an options object to indicate whether
`func` should be invoked on the leading and/or trailing edge of the `wait`
timeout. The `func` is invoked with the last arguments provided to the
throttled function. Subsequent calls to the throttled function return the
result of the last `func` invocation.

**Note:** If `leading` and `trailing` options are `true`, `func` is
invoked on the trailing edge of the timeout only if the throttled function
is invoked more than once during the `wait` timeout.

See [David Corbacho's article](https://css-tricks.com/debouncing-throttling-explained-examples/)
for details over the differences between `_.throttle` and `_.debounce`.

parameters.name: wait
parameters.description: The number of milliseconds to throttle invocations to.

parameters.name: options.leading
parameters.description: Specify invoking on the leading edge of the timeout.

parameters.name: options.trailing
parameters.description: Specify invoking on the trailing edge of the timeout.

functions.name: unary
functions.description:
Creates a function that accepts up to one argument, ignoring any
additional arguments.

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The function to cap arguments for.

functions.name: wrap
functions.description:
Creates a function that provides `value` to the wrapper function as its
first argument. Any additional arguments provided to the function are
appended to those provided to the wrapper function. The wrapper is invoked
with the `this` binding of the created function.

functions.name: castArray
functions.description: Casts `value` as an array if it's not one.

functions.name: clone
functions.description:
Creates a shallow clone of `value`.

**Note:** This method is loosely based on the
[structured clone algorithm](https://mdn.io/Structured_clone_algorithm)
and supports cloning arrays, array buffers, booleans, date objects, maps,
numbers, `Object` objects, regexes, sets, strings, symbols, and typed
arrays. The own enumerable properties of `arguments` objects are cloned
as plain objects. An empty object is returned for uncloneable values such
as error objects, functions, DOM nodes, and WeakMaps.

functions.name: cloneWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.clone` except that it accepts `customizer` which
is invoked to produce the cloned value. If `customizer` returns `undefined`,
cloning is handled by the method instead. The `customizer` is invoked with
up to four arguments; (value [, index|key, object, stack]).

functions.name: cloneDeep
functions.description: This method is like `_.clone` except that it recursively clones `value`.

functions.name: cloneDeepWith
functions.description: This method is like `_.cloneWith` except that it recursively clones `value`.

functions.name: eq
functions.description:
Performs a
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
comparison between two values to determine if they are equivalent.

returns.description: Returns `true` if the values are equivalent, else `false`.

functions.name: gt
functions.description: Checks if `value` is greater than `other`.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is greater than `other`,
 else `false`.

functions.name: gte
functions.description: Checks if `value` is greater than or equal to `other`.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is greater than or equal to
 `other`, else `false`.

functions.name: isArguments
functions.description: Checks if `value` is likely an `arguments` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isArrayBuffer
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as an `ArrayBuffer` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isArrayLike
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is array-like. A value is considered array-like if it's
not a function and has a `value.length` that's an integer greater than or
equal to `0` and less than or equal to `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`.

functions.name: isArrayLikeObject
functions.description:
This method is like `_.isArrayLike` except that it also checks if `value`
is an object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is an array-like object,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isBoolean
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a boolean primitive or object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isDate
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `Date` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isElement
functions.description: Checks if `value` is likely a DOM element.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a DOM element,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isEmpty
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is an empty object, collection, map, or set.

Objects are considered empty if they have no own enumerable string keyed
properties.

Array-like values such as `arguments` objects, arrays, buffers, strings, or
jQuery-like collections are considered empty if they have a `length` of `0`.
Similarly, maps and sets are considered empty if they have a `size` of `0`.

functions.name: isEqual
functions.description:
Performs a deep comparison between two values to determine if they are
equivalent.

**Note:** This method supports comparing arrays, array buffers, booleans,
date objects, error objects, maps, numbers, `Object` objects, regexes,
sets, strings, symbols, and typed arrays. `Object` objects are compared
by their own, not inherited, enumerable properties. Functions and DOM
nodes are **not** supported.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if the values are equivalent,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isEqualWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.isEqual` except that it accepts `customizer` which
is invoked to compare values. If `customizer` returns `undefined`, comparisons
are handled by the method instead. The `customizer` is invoked with up to
six arguments: (objValue, othValue [, index|key, object, other, stack]).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if the values are equivalent,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isError
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is an `Error`, `EvalError`, `RangeError`, `ReferenceError`,
`SyntaxError`, `TypeError`, or `URIError` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is an error object,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isFinite
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is a finite primitive number.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`Number.isFinite`](https://mdn.io/Number/isFinite).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a finite number,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isFunction
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `Function` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isInteger
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is an integer.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`Number.isInteger`](https://mdn.io/Number/isInteger).

returns.description: Returns `true` if `value` is an integer, else `false`.

functions.name: isLength
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is a valid array-like length.

**Note:** This function is loosely based on
[`ToLength`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-tolength).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a valid length,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isObject
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is the
[language type](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-ecmascript-language-types)
of `Object`. (e.g. arrays, functions, objects, regexes, `new Number(0)`, and `new String('')`)

returns.description: Returns `true` if `value` is an object, else `false`.

functions.name: isObjectLike
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is object-like. A value is object-like if it's not `null`
and has a `typeof` result of "object".

functions.name: isMap
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `Map` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isMatch
functions.description:
Performs a partial deep comparison between `object` and `source` to
determine if `object` contains equivalent property values. This method is
equivalent to a `_.matches` function when `source` is partially applied.

**Note:** This method supports comparing the same values as `_.isEqual`.

parameters.name: source
parameters.description: The object of property values to match.

returns.description: Returns `true` if `object` is a match, else `false`.

functions.name: isMatchWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.isMatch` except that it accepts `customizer` which
is invoked to compare values. If `customizer` returns `undefined`, comparisons
are handled by the method instead. The `customizer` is invoked with five
arguments: (objValue, srcValue, index|key, object, source).

parameters.name: source
parameters.description: The object of property values to match.

returns.description: Returns `true` if `object` is a match, else `false`.

functions.name: isNaN
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is `NaN`.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`Number.isNaN`](https://mdn.io/Number/isNaN) and is not the same as
global [`isNaN`](https://mdn.io/isNaN) which returns `true` for
`undefined` and other non-number values.

functions.name: isNative
functions.description: Checks if `value` is a native function.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a native function,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isNull
functions.description: Checks if `value` is `null`.

functions.name: isNil
functions.description: Checks if `value` is `null` or `undefined`.

functions.name: isNumber
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is classified as a `Number` primitive or object.

**Note:** To exclude `Infinity`, `-Infinity`, and `NaN`, which are
classified as numbers, use the `_.isFinite` method.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isPlainObject
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is a plain object, that is, an object created by the
`Object` constructor or one with a `[[Prototype]]` of `null`.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a plain object,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isRegExp
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `RegExp` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isSafeInteger
functions.description:
Checks if `value` is a safe integer. An integer is safe if it's an IEEE-754
double precision number which isn't the result of a rounded unsafe integer.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`Number.isSafeInteger`](https://mdn.io/Number/isSafeInteger).

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is a safe integer,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isSet
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `Set` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isString
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `String` primitive or object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isSymbol
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `Symbol` primitive or object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isTypedArray
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a typed array.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isUndefined
functions.description: Checks if `value` is `undefined`.

functions.name: isWeakMap
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `WeakMap` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: isWeakSet
functions.description: Checks if `value` is classified as a `WeakSet` object.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is correctly classified,
 else `false`.

functions.name: lt
functions.description: Checks if `value` is less than `other`.

returns.description:

 else `false`.

functions.name: lte
functions.description: Checks if `value` is less than or equal to `other`.

returns.description:
Returns `true` if `value` is less than or equal to
 `other`, else `false`.

functions.name: toArray
functions.description: Converts `value` to an array.

functions.name: toInteger
functions.description:
