[`ToInteger`](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-tointeger).

functions.name: toLength
functions.description:
Converts `value` to an integer suitable for use as the length of an
array-like object.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`ToLength`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-tolength).

functions.name: toNumber
functions.description: Converts `value` to a number.

functions.name: toPlainObject
functions.description:
Converts `value` to a plain object flattening inherited enumerable string
keyed properties of `value` to own properties of the plain object.

functions.name: toSafeInteger
functions.description:
Converts `value` to a safe integer. A safe integer can be compared and
represented correctly.

functions.name: toString
functions.description:
Converts `value` to a string. An empty string is returned for `null`
and `undefined` values. The sign of `-0` is preserved.

functions.name: create
functions.description:
Creates an object that inherits from the `prototype` object. If a
`properties` object is given, its own enumerable string keyed properties
are assigned to the created object.

parameters.name: properties
parameters.description: The properties to assign to the object.

functions.name: findKey
functions.description:
This method is like `_.find` except that it returns the key of the first
element `predicate` returns truthy for instead of the element itself.

returns.description:
Returns the key of the matched element,
 else `undefined`.

functions.name: findLastKey
functions.description:
This method is like `_.findKey` except that it iterates over elements of
a collection in the opposite order.

returns.description:
Returns the key of the matched element,
 else `undefined`.

functions.name: forIn
functions.description:
Iterates over own and inherited enumerable string keyed properties of an
object and invokes `iteratee` for each property. The iteratee is invoked
with three arguments: (value, key, object). Iteratee functions may exit
iteration early by explicitly returning `false`.

functions.name: forInRight
functions.description:
This method is like `_.forIn` except that it iterates over properties of
`object` in the opposite order.

functions.name: forOwn
functions.description:
Iterates over own enumerable string keyed properties of an object and
invokes `iteratee` for each property. The iteratee is invoked with three
arguments: (value, key, object). Iteratee functions may exit iteration
early by explicitly returning `false`.

functions.name: forOwnRight
functions.description:
This method is like `_.forOwn` except that it iterates over properties of
`object` in the opposite order.

functions.name: functions
functions.description:
Creates an array of function property names from own enumerable properties
of `object`.

returns.description: Returns the new array of property names.

functions.name: functionsIn
functions.description:
Creates an array of function property names from own and inherited
enumerable properties of `object`.

returns.description: Returns the new array of property names.

functions.name: get
functions.description:
Gets the value at `path` of `object`. If the resolved value is
`undefined`, the `defaultValue` is used in its place.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to get.

parameters.name: defaultValue
parameters.description: The value returned for `undefined` resolved values.

functions.name: has
functions.description: Checks if `path` is a direct property of `object`.

functions.name: hasIn
functions.description: Checks if `path` is a direct or inherited property of `object`.

functions.name: keys
functions.description:
Creates an array of the own enumerable property names of `object`.

**Note:** Non-object values are coerced to objects. See the
[ES spec](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-object.keys)
for more details.

returns.description: Returns the array of property names.

functions.name: keysIn
functions.description:
Creates an array of the own and inherited enumerable property names of `object`.

**Note:** Non-object values are coerced to objects.

returns.description: Returns the array of property names.

functions.name: mapKeys
functions.description:
The opposite of `_.mapValues`; this method creates an object with the
same values as `object` and keys generated by running each own enumerable
string keyed property of `object` thru `iteratee`. The iteratee is invoked
with three arguments: (value, key, object).

functions.name: mapValues
functions.description:
Creates an object with the same keys as `object` and values generated
by running each own enumerable string keyed property of `object` thru
`iteratee`. The iteratee is invoked with three arguments:
(value, key, object).

functions.name: omitBy
functions.description:
The opposite of `_.pickBy`; this method creates an object composed of
the own and inherited enumerable string keyed properties of `object` that
`predicate` doesn't return truthy for. The predicate is invoked with two
arguments: (value, key).

functions.name: pickBy
functions.description:
Creates an object composed of the `object` properties `predicate` returns
truthy for. The predicate is invoked with two arguments: (value, key).

functions.name: result
functions.description:
This method is like `_.get` except that if the resolved value is a
function it's invoked with the `this` binding of its parent object and
its result is returned.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to resolve.

parameters.name: defaultValue
parameters.description: The value returned for `undefined` resolved values.

functions.name: set
functions.description:
Sets the value at `path` of `object`. If a portion of `path` doesn't exist,
it's created. Arrays are created for missing index properties while objects
are created for all other missing properties. Use `_.setWith` to customize
`path` creation.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to set.

functions.name: setWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.set` except that it accepts `customizer` which is
invoked to produce the objects of `path`.  If `customizer` returns `undefined`
path creation is handled by the method instead. The `customizer` is invoked
with three arguments: (nsValue, key, nsObject).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to set.

parameters.name: customizer
parameters.description: The function to customize assigned values.

functions.name: entries
functions.description:
Creates an array of own enumerable string keyed-value pairs for `object`
which can be consumed by `_.fromPairs`.

returns.description: Returns the new array of key-value pairs.

functions.name: entriesIn
functions.description:
Creates an array of own and inherited enumerable string keyed-value pairs
for `object` which can be consumed by `_.fromPairs`.

returns.description: Returns the new array of key-value pairs.

functions.name: transform
functions.description:
An alternative to `_.reduce`; this method transforms `object` to a new
`accumulator` object which is the result of running each of its own
enumerable string keyed properties thru `iteratee`, with each invocation
potentially mutating the `accumulator` object. The iteratee is invoked
with four arguments: (accumulator, value, key, object). Iteratee functions
may exit iteration early by explicitly returning `false`.

functions.name: unset
functions.description:
Removes the property at `path` of `object`.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to unset.

returns.description: Returns `true` if the property is deleted, else `false`.

functions.name: update
functions.description:
This method is like `_.set` except that accepts `updater` to produce the
value to set. Use `_.updateWith` to customize `path` creation. The `updater`
is invoked with one argument: (value).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to set.

parameters.name: updater
parameters.description: The function to produce the updated value.

functions.name: updateWith
functions.description:
This method is like `_.update` except that it accepts `customizer` which is
invoked to produce the objects of `path`.  If `customizer` returns `undefined`
path creation is handled by the method instead. The `customizer` is invoked
with three arguments: (nsValue, key, nsObject).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to set.

parameters.name: updater
parameters.description: The function to produce the updated value.

parameters.name: customizer
parameters.description: The function to customize assigned values.

functions.name: values
functions.description:
Creates an array of the own enumerable string keyed property values of `object`.

**Note:** Non-object values are coerced to objects.

returns.description: Returns the array of property values.

functions.name: valuesIn
functions.description:
Creates an array of the own and inherited enumerable string keyed property
values of `object`.

**Note:** Non-object values are coerced to objects.

returns.description: Returns the array of property values.

functions.name: clamp
functions.description: Clamps `number` within the inclusive `lower` and `upper` bounds.

functions.name: inRange
functions.description:
Checks if `n` is between `start` and up to but not including, `end`. If
`end` is not specified, it's set to `start` with `start` then set to `0`.
If `start` is greater than `end` the params are swapped to support
negative ranges.

returns.description: Returns `true` if `number` is in the range, else `false`.

functions.name: random
functions.description:
Produces a random number between the inclusive `lower` and `upper` bounds.
If only one argument is provided a number between `0` and the given number
is returned. If `floating` is `true`, or either `lower` or `upper` are
floats, a floating-point number is returned instead of an integer.

**Note:** JavaScript follows the IEEE-754 standard for resolving
floating-point values which can produce unexpected results.

functions.name: capitalize
functions.description:
Converts the first character of `string` to upper case and the remaining
to lower case.

functions.name: deburr
functions.description:
Deburrs `string` by converting
[latin-1 supplementary letters](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin-1_Supplement_(Unicode_block)#Character_table)
to basic latin letters and removing
[combining diacritical marks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combining_Diacritical_Marks).

functions.name: endsWith
functions.description: Checks if `string` ends with the given target string.

functions.name: escape
functions.description:
Converts the characters "&", "<", ">", '"', "'", and "\`" in `string` to
their corresponding HTML entities.

**Note:** No other characters are escaped. To escape additional
characters use a third-party library like [_he_](https://mths.be/he).

Though the ">" character is escaped for symmetry, characters like
">" and "/" don't need escaping in HTML and have no special meaning
unless they're part of a tag or unquoted attribute value. See
[Mathias Bynens's article](https://mathiasbynens.be/notes/ambiguous-ampersands)
(under "semi-related fun fact") for more details.

Backticks are escaped because in IE < 9, they can break out of
attribute values or HTML comments. See [#59](https://html5sec.org/#59),
[#102](https://html5sec.org/#102), [#108](https://html5sec.org/#108), and
[#133](https://html5sec.org/#133) of the
[HTML5 Security Cheatsheet](https://html5sec.org/) for more details.

When working with HTML you should always
[quote attribute values](http://wonko.com/post/html-escaping) to reduce
XSS vectors.

functions.name: escapeRegExp
functions.description:
Escapes the `RegExp` special characters "^", "$", "\", ".", "*", "+",
"?", "(", ")", "[", "]", "{", "}", and "|" in `string`.

functions.name: pad
functions.description:
Pads `string` on the left and right sides if it's shorter than `length`.
Padding characters are truncated if they can't be evenly divided by `length`.

functions.name: padEnd
functions.description:
Pads `string` on the right side if it's shorter than `length`. Padding
characters are truncated if they exceed `length`.

functions.name: padStart
functions.description:
Pads `string` on the left side if it's shorter than `length`. Padding
characters are truncated if they exceed `length`.

functions.name: parseInt
functions.description:
Converts `string` to an integer of the specified radix. If `radix` is
`undefined` or `0`, a `radix` of `10` is used unless `value` is a
hexadecimal, in which case a `radix` of `16` is used.

**Note:** This method aligns with the
[ES5 implementation](https://es5.github.io/#x15.1.2.2) of `parseInt`.

functions.name: repeat
functions.description: Repeats the given string `n` times.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of times to repeat the string.

functions.name: replace
functions.description:
Replaces matches for `pattern` in `string` with `replacement`.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`String#replace`](https://mdn.io/String/replace).

functions.name: split
functions.description:
Splits `string` by `separator`.

**Note:** This method is based on
[`String#split`](https://mdn.io/String/split).

parameters.name: separator
parameters.description: The separator pattern to split by.

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: The length to truncate results to.

returns.description: Returns the new array of string segments.

functions.name: startsWith
functions.description: Checks if `string` starts with the given target string.

functions.name: template
functions.description:
Creates a compiled template function that can interpolate data properties
in "interpolate" delimiters, HTML-escape interpolated data properties in
"escape" delimiters, and execute JavaScript in "evaluate" delimiters. Data
properties may be accessed as free variables in the template. If a setting
object is given, it takes precedence over `_.templateSettings` values.

**Note:** In the development build `_.template` utilizes
[sourceURLs](http://www.html5rocks.com/en/tutorials/developertools/sourcemaps/#toc-sourceurl)
for easier debugging.

For more information on precompiling templates see
[lodash's custom builds documentation](https://lodash.com/custom-builds).

For more information on Chrome extension sandboxes see
[Chrome's extensions documentation](https://developer.chrome.com/extensions/sandboxingEval).

parameters.name: options.imports
parameters.description: An object to import into the template as free variables.

parameters.name: options.sourceURL
parameters.description: The sourceURL of the compiled template.

functions.name: toLower
functions.description:
Converts `string`, as a whole, to lower case just like
[String#toLowerCase](https://mdn.io/toLowerCase).

functions.name: toUpper
functions.description:
Converts `string`, as a whole, to upper case just like
[String#toUpperCase](https://mdn.io/toUpperCase).

functions.name: trim
functions.description: Removes leading and trailing whitespace or specified characters from `string`.

functions.name: trimEnd
functions.description: Removes trailing whitespace or specified characters from `string`.

functions.name: trimStart
functions.description: Removes leading whitespace or specified characters from `string`.

functions.name: truncate
functions.description:
Truncates `string` if it's longer than the given maximum string length.
The last characters of the truncated string are replaced with the omission
string which defaults to "...".

parameters.name: options.omission
parameters.description: The string to indicate text is omitted.

parameters.name: options.separator
parameters.description: The separator pattern to truncate to.

functions.name: unescape
functions.description:
The inverse of `_.escape`; this method converts the HTML entities
`&`, `<`, `>`, `"`, `'`, and ``` in `string` to
their corresponding characters.

**Note:** No other HTML entities are unescaped. To unescape additional
HTML entities use a third-party library like [_he_](https://mths.be/he).

functions.name: words
functions.description: Splits `string` into an array of its words.

functions.name: cond
functions.description:
Creates a function that iterates over `pairs` and invokes the corresponding
function of the first predicate to return truthy. The predicate-function
pairs are invoked with the `this` binding and arguments of the created
function.

functions.name: conforms
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes the predicate properties of `source` with
the corresponding property values of a given object, returning `true` if
all predicates return truthy, else `false`.

parameters.name: source
parameters.description: The object of property predicates to conform to.

functions.name: constant
functions.description: Creates a function that returns `value`.

parameters.name: value
parameters.description: The value to return from the new function.

functions.name: identity
functions.description: This method returns the first argument given to it.

functions.name: iteratee
functions.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with the arguments of the created
function. If `func` is a property name, the created function returns the
property value for a given element. If `func` is an array or object, the
created function returns `true` for elements that contain the equivalent
source properties, otherwise it returns `false`.

parameters.name: func
parameters.description: The value to convert to a callback.

functions.name: matches
functions.description:
Creates a function that performs a partial deep comparison between a given
object and `source`, returning `true` if the given object has equivalent
property values, else `false`. The created function is equivalent to
`_.isMatch` with a `source` partially applied.

**Note:** This method supports comparing the same values as `_.isEqual`.

parameters.name: source
parameters.description: The object of property values to match.

functions.name: matchesProperty
functions.description:
Creates a function that performs a partial deep comparison between the
value at `path` of a given object to `srcValue`, returning `true` if the
object value is equivalent, else `false`.

**Note:** This method supports comparing the same values as `_.isEqual`.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to get.

functions.name: mixin
functions.description:
Adds all own enumerable string keyed function properties of a source
object to the destination object. If `object` is a function, then methods
are added to its prototype as well.

**Note:** Use `_.runInContext` to create a pristine `lodash` function to
avoid conflicts caused by modifying the original.

parameters.name: source
parameters.description: The object of functions to add.

functions.name: noConflict
functions.description:
Reverts the `_` variable to its previous value and returns a reference to
the `lodash` function.

functions.name: noop
functions.description:
A no-operation function that returns `undefined` regardless of the
arguments it receives.

functions.name: nthArg
functions.description:
Creates a function that returns its nth argument. If `n` is negative,
the nth argument from the end is returned.

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The index of the argument to return.

functions.name: property
functions.description: Creates a function that returns the value at `path` of a given object.

parameters.name: path
parameters.description: The path of the property to get.

functions.name: propertyOf
functions.description:
The opposite of `_.property`; this method creates a function that returns
the value at a given path of `object`.

functions.name: times
functions.description:
Invokes the iteratee `n` times, returning an array of the results of
each invocation. The iteratee is invoked with one argument; (index).

parameters.name: n
parameters.description: The number of times to invoke `iteratee`.

functions.name: toPath
functions.description: Converts `value` to a property path array.

returns.description: Returns the new property path array.

functions.name: uniqueId
functions.description: Generates a unique ID. If `prefix` is given, the ID is appended to it.

parameters.name: prefix
parameters.description: The value to prefix the ID with.

functions.name: max
functions.description:
Computes the maximum value of `array`. If `array` is empty or falsey,
`undefined` is returned.

functions.name: maxBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.max` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element in `array` to generate the criterion by which
the value is ranked. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

functions.name: mean
functions.description: Computes the mean of the values in `array`.

functions.name: meanBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.mean` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element in `array` to generate the value to be averaged.
The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

functions.name: min
functions.description:
Computes the minimum value of `array`. If `array` is empty or falsey,
`undefined` is returned.

functions.name: minBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.min` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element in `array` to generate the criterion by which
the value is ranked. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

functions.name: sum
functions.description: Computes the sum of the values in `array`.

functions.name: sumBy
functions.description:
This method is like `_.sum` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element in `array` to generate the value to be summed.
The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: difference
properties.description:
Creates an array of unique `array` values not included in the other given
arrays using [`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons. The order of result values is determined by the
order they occur in the first array.

properties.name: differenceBy
properties.description:
This method is like `_.difference` except that it accepts `iteratee` which
is invoked for each element of `array` and `values` to generate the criterion
by which they're compared. Result values are chosen from the first array.
The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: differenceWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.difference` except that it accepts `comparator`
which is invoked to compare elements of `array` to `values`. Result values
are chosen from the first array. The comparator is invoked with two arguments:
(arrVal, othVal).

properties.name: intersection
properties.description:
Creates an array of unique values that are included in all given arrays
using [`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons. The order of result values is determined by the
order they occur in the first array.

properties.name: intersectionBy
properties.description:
This method is like `_.intersection` except that it accepts `iteratee`
which is invoked for each element of each `arrays` to generate the criterion
by which they're compared. Result values are chosen from the first array.
The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: intersectionWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.intersection` except that it accepts `comparator`
which is invoked to compare elements of `arrays`. Result values are chosen
from the first array. The comparator is invoked with two arguments:
(arrVal, othVal).

properties.name: pull
properties.description:
Removes all given values from `array` using
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons.

**Note:** Unlike `_.without`, this method mutates `array`. Use `_.remove`
to remove elements from an array by predicate.

properties.name: pullAt
properties.description:
Removes elements from `array` corresponding to `indexes` and returns an
array of removed elements.

**Note:** Unlike `_.at`, this method mutates `array`.

properties.name: union
properties.description:
Creates an array of unique values, in order, from all given arrays using
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons.

properties.name: unionBy
properties.description:
This method is like `_.union` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element of each `arrays` to generate the criterion by
which uniqueness is computed. The iteratee is invoked with one argument:
(value).

properties.name: unionWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.union` except that it accepts `comparator` which
is invoked to compare elements of `arrays`. The comparator is invoked
with two arguments: (arrVal, othVal).

properties.name: without
properties.description:
Creates an array excluding all given values using
[`SameValueZero`](http://ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-samevaluezero)
for equality comparisons.

properties.name: xor
properties.description:
Creates an array of unique values that is the
[symmetric difference](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_difference)
of the given arrays. The order of result values is determined by the order
they occur in the arrays.

properties.name: xorBy
properties.description:
This method is like `_.xor` except that it accepts `iteratee` which is
invoked for each element of each `arrays` to generate the criterion by
which by which they're compared. The iteratee is invoked with one argument:
(value).

properties.name: xorWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.xor` except that it accepts `comparator` which is
invoked to compare elements of `arrays`. The comparator is invoked with
two arguments: (arrVal, othVal).

properties.name: zip
properties.description:
Creates an array of grouped elements, the first of which contains the
first elements of the given arrays, the second of which contains the
second elements of the given arrays, and so on.

properties.name: zipWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.zip` except that it accepts `iteratee` to specify
how grouped values should be combined. The iteratee is invoked with the
elements of each group: (...group).

properties.name: at
properties.description: This method is the wrapper version of `_.at`.

properties.name: chain
properties.description: Creates a `lodash` wrapper instance with explicit method chain sequences enabled.

properties.name: commit
properties.description: Executes the chain sequence and returns the wrapped result.

properties.name: next
properties.description:
Gets the next value on a wrapped object following the
[iterator protocol](https://mdn.io/iteration_protocols#iterator).

properties.name: plant
properties.description: Creates a clone of the chain sequence planting `value` as the wrapped value.

properties.name: reverse
properties.description:
This method is the wrapper version of `_.reverse`.

**Note:** This method mutates the wrapped array.

properties.name: value
properties.description: Executes the chain sequence to resolve the unwrapped value.

properties.name: countBy
properties.description:
Creates an object composed of keys generated from the results of running
each element of `collection` thru `iteratee`. The corresponding value of
each key is the number of times the key was returned by `iteratee`. The
iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: groupBy
properties.description:
Creates an object composed of keys generated from the results of running
each element of `collection` thru `iteratee`. The order of grouped values
is determined by the order they occur in `collection`. The corresponding
value of each key is an array of elements responsible for generating the
key. The iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: invokeMap
properties.description:
Invokes the method at `path` of each element in `collection`, returning
an array of the results of each invoked method. Any additional arguments
are provided to each invoked method. If `methodName` is a function, it's
invoked for and `this` bound to, each element in `collection`.

properties.name: keyBy
properties.description:
Creates an object composed of keys generated from the results of running
each element of `collection` thru `iteratee`. The corresponding value of
each key is the last element responsible for generating the key. The
iteratee is invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: partition
properties.description:
Creates an array of elements split into two groups, the first of which
contains elements `predicate` returns truthy for, the second of which
contains elements `predicate` returns falsey for. The predicate is
invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: sortBy
properties.description:
Creates an array of elements, sorted in ascending order by the results of
running each element in a collection thru each iteratee. This method
performs a stable sort, that is, it preserves the original sort order of
equal elements. The iteratees are invoked with one argument: (value).

properties.name: now
properties.description:
Gets the timestamp of the number of milliseconds that have elapsed since
the Unix epoch (1 January 1970 00:00:00 UTC).

properties.name: bind
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with the `this` binding of `thisArg`
and `partials` prepended to the arguments it receives.

The `_.bind.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic builds,
may be used as a placeholder for partially applied arguments.

**Note:** Unlike native `Function#bind` this method doesn't set the "length"
property of bound functions.

properties.name: bindKey
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes the method at `object[key]` with `partials`
prepended to the arguments it receives.

This method differs from `_.bind` by allowing bound functions to reference
methods that may be redefined or don't yet exist. See
[Peter Michaux's article](http://peter.michaux.ca/articles/lazy-function-definition-pattern)
for more details.

The `_.bindKey.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic
builds, may be used as a placeholder for partially applied arguments.

properties.name: defer
properties.description:
Defers invoking the `func` until the current call stack has cleared. Any
additional arguments are provided to `func` when it's invoked.

properties.name: delay
properties.description:
Invokes `func` after `wait` milliseconds. Any additional arguments are
provided to `func` when it's invoked.

properties.name: overArgs
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with arguments transformed by
corresponding `transforms`.

properties.name: partial
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with `partials` prepended to the
arguments it receives. This method is like `_.bind` except it does **not**
alter the `this` binding.

The `_.partial.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic
builds, may be used as a placeholder for partially applied arguments.

**Note:** This method doesn't set the "length" property of partially
applied functions.

properties.name: partialRight
properties.description:
This method is like `_.partial` except that partially applied arguments
are appended to the arguments it receives.

The `_.partialRight.placeholder` value, which defaults to `_` in monolithic
builds, may be used as a placeholder for partially applied arguments.

**Note:** This method doesn't set the "length" property of partially
applied functions.

properties.name: rearg
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes `func` with arguments arranged according
to the specified `indexes` where the argument value at the first index is
provided as the first argument, the argument value at the second index is
provided as the second argument, and so on.

properties.name: isArray
properties.description: Checks if `value` is classified as an `Array` object.

properties.name: isBuffer
properties.description: Checks if `value` is a buffer.

properties.name: assign
properties.description:
Assigns own enumerable string keyed properties of source objects to the
destination object. Source objects are applied from left to right.
Subsequent sources overwrite property assignments of previous sources.

**Note:** This method mutates `object` and is loosely based on
[`Object.assign`](https://mdn.io/Object/assign).

properties.name: extend
properties.description:
This method is like `_.assign` except that it iterates over own and
inherited source properties.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: extendWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.assignIn` except that it accepts `customizer`
which is invoked to produce the assigned values. If `customizer` returns
`undefined`, assignment is handled by the method instead. The `customizer`
is invoked with five arguments: (objValue, srcValue, key, object, source).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: assignWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.assign` except that it accepts `customizer`
which is invoked to produce the assigned values. If `customizer` returns
`undefined`, assignment is handled by the method instead. The `customizer`
is invoked with five arguments: (objValue, srcValue, key, object, source).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: at
properties.description: Creates an array of values corresponding to `paths` of `object`.

properties.name: defaults
properties.description:
Assigns own and inherited enumerable string keyed properties of source
objects to the destination object for all destination properties that
resolve to `undefined`. Source objects are applied from left to right.
Once a property is set, additional values of the same property are ignored.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: defaultsDeep
properties.description:
This method is like `_.defaults` except that it recursively assigns
default properties.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: invert
properties.description:
Creates an object composed of the inverted keys and values of `object`.
If `object` contains duplicate values, subsequent values overwrite
property assignments of previous values.

properties.name: invertBy
properties.description:
This method is like `_.invert` except that the inverted object is generated
from the results of running each element of `object` thru `iteratee`. The
corresponding inverted value of each inverted key is an array of keys
responsible for generating the inverted value. The iteratee is invoked
with one argument: (value).

properties.name: invoke
properties.description: Invokes the method at `path` of `object`.

properties.name: merge
properties.description:
This method is like `_.assign` except that it recursively merges own and
inherited enumerable string keyed properties of source objects into the
destination object. Source properties that resolve to `undefined` are
skipped if a destination value exists. Array and plain object properties
are merged recursively.Other objects and value types are overridden by
assignment. Source objects are applied from left to right. Subsequent
sources overwrite property assignments of previous sources.

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: mergeWith
properties.description:
This method is like `_.merge` except that it accepts `customizer` which
is invoked to produce the merged values of the destination and source
properties. If `customizer` returns `undefined`, merging is handled by the
method instead. The `customizer` is invoked with seven arguments:
(objValue, srcValue, key, object, source, stack).

**Note:** This method mutates `object`.

properties.name: omit
properties.description:
The opposite of `_.pick`; this method creates an object composed of the
own and inherited enumerable string keyed properties of `object` that are
not omitted.

properties.name: pick
properties.description: Creates an object composed of the picked `object` properties.

properties.name: camelCase
properties.description: Converts `string` to [camel case](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CamelCase).

properties.name: kebabCase
properties.description:
Converts `string` to
[kebab case](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letter_case#Special_case_styles).

properties.name: lowerCase
properties.description: Converts `string`, as space separated words, to lower case.

properties.name: lowerFirst
properties.description: Converts the first character of `string` to lower case.

properties.name: snakeCase
properties.description:
Converts `string` to
[snake case](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snake_case).

properties.name: startCase
properties.description:
Converts `string` to
[start case](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Letter_case#Stylistic_or_specialised_usage).

properties.name: upperCase
properties.description: Converts `string`, as space separated words, to upper case.

properties.name: upperFirst
properties.description: Converts the first character of `string` to upper case.

properties.name: attempt
properties.description:
Attempts to invoke `func`, returning either the result or the caught error
object. Any additional arguments are provided to `func` when it's invoked.

properties.name: bindAll
properties.description:
Binds methods of an object to the object itself, overwriting the existing
method.

**Note:** This method doesn't set the "length" property of bound functions.

properties.name: flow
properties.description:
Creates a function that returns the result of invoking the given functions
with the `this` binding of the created function, where each successive
invocation is supplied the return value of the previous.

properties.name: flowRight
properties.description:
This method is like `_.flow` except that it creates a function that
invokes the given functions from right to left.

properties.name: method
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes the method at `path` of a given object.
Any additional arguments are provided to the invoked method.

properties.name: methodOf
properties.description:
The opposite of `_.method`; this method creates a function that invokes
the method at a given path of `object`. Any additional arguments are
provided to the invoked method.

properties.name: over
properties.description:
Creates a function that invokes `iteratees` with the arguments it receives
and returns their results.

properties.name: overEvery
properties.description:
Creates a function that checks if **all** of the `predicates` return
truthy when invoked with the arguments it receives.

properties.name: overSome
properties.description:
Creates a function that checks if **any** of the `predicates` return
truthy when invoked with the arguments it receives.

properties.name: range
properties.description:
Creates an array of numbers (positive and/or negative) progressing from
`start` up to, but not including, `end`. A step of `-1` is used if a negative
`start` is specified without an `end` or `step`. If `end` is not specified,
it's set to `start` with `start` then set to `0`.

**Note:** JavaScript follows the IEEE-754 standard for resolving
floating-point values which can produce unexpected results.

properties.name: rangeRight
properties.description:
This method is like `_.range` except that it populates values in
descending order.

properties.name: add
properties.description: Adds two numbers.

properties.name: ceil
properties.description: Computes `number` rounded up to `precision`.

properties.name: divide
properties.description: Divide two numbers.

properties.name: floor
properties.description: Computes `number` rounded down to `precision`.

properties.name: multiply
properties.description: Multiply two numbers.

properties.name: round
properties.description: Computes `number` rounded to `precision`.

properties.name: subtract
properties.description: Subtract two numbers.
